#compdef excel-mcp-server
# ============================================================================
# excel-mcp-server - Model Context Protocol
#                     (MCP) server for Excel
#                     file read/write via AI
#                     agents
#                     (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : negokaz
# Upstream: https://github.com/negokaz/excel-mcp-server
# npm pkg : @negokaz/excel-mcp-server (Node
#           launcher wrapping the Go binary)
#
# `excel-mcp-server` is an MCP (Model
# Context Protocol) server exposing Excel
# file operations to AI agents like Claude
# Desktop + Cursor + Windsurf + other MCP-
# capable AI assistants. The server runs as
# a stdio-based subprocess that the AI
# client launches + communicates with via
# JSON-RPC over stdin/stdout.
#
# Architecture:
#   1. **MCP server over stdio** (uses
#      mark3labs/mcp-go for the MCP
#      protocol implementation)
#   2. **excelize backend** (xuri/excelize/
#      v2 for XLSX read/write)
#   3. **Windows-specific tools** (when
#      running on Windows: live screen
#      capture of open Excel windows via
#      go-ole for COM automation)
#   4. **Node launcher wrapper**
#     (npm install @negokaz/excel-mcp-
#     server downloads the Go binary +
#     wraps it in a Node script for
#     cross-platform installation; can
#     also be used directly via the Go
#     binary)
#
# MCP tools provided:
#   - **excel_describe_sheets** - list
#     all sheets in an Excel workbook with
#     metadata (dimensions + headers)
#   - **excel_read_sheet** - read sheet
#     data into structured JSON
#   - **excel_write_to_sheet** - write
#     data to a specific cell range
#   - **excel_create_table** - create
#     an Excel table with header row +
#     styling
#   - **excel_copy_sheet** - duplicate
#     a sheet within or across workbooks
#   - **excel_format_range** - apply
#     cell formatting (number format +
#     fill + font + border)
#   - **excel_screen_capture** (Windows
#     only) - capture screenshot of
#     currently-open Excel window
#
# Distinguishing features:
#   - **MCP-native** (designed for AI agent
#     integration via the canonical MCP
#     protocol)
#   - **Read + write** (not just read like
#     many Excel CLIs; AI can modify
#     workbooks)
#   - **Windows COM integration** (screen
#     capture tool uses Excel's COM
#     automation interface)
#   - **Single binary** (Go cross-compiles
#     to all platforms; no Excel/Office
#     runtime required on Linux + macOS)
#   - **Both Go binary + npm package**
#     (npm install for AI agents that
#     prefer JavaScript-managed tooling;
#     direct binary for native
#     installations)
#
# Use cases:
#   - **AI-assisted financial modeling**
#     (Claude/GPT-4 reads spreadsheet
#     data + suggests formula changes)
#   - **Data analysis workflows** (AI
#     agent loads CSV data + creates
#     formatted Excel reports)
#   - **Excel report automation** (AI
#     agent generates reports from
#     templates)
#   - **Spreadsheet review** (AI agent
#     audits formulas + suggests
#     improvements)
#   - **Data migration** (AI-orchestrated
#     conversion between spreadsheet
#     formats + data normalization)
#
# Usage:
#   excel-mcp-server
#
# The server has no command-line flags -
# it runs as a stdio-based MCP server.
# Configuration is via the AI client's
# MCP configuration file (typically
# claude_desktop_config.json or similar).
#
# Standard flags (inherited from Go
# standard handling):
#   -h, --help                     - show
#                                     help
#                                     (not
#                                     yet
#                                     implemented;
#                                     server
#                                     starts
#                                     immediately
#                                     on
#                                     invocation)
#
# Example AI client configurations:
#
#   # Claude Desktop (~/.config/claude/
#   # claude_desktop_config.json on Linux/
#   # macOS; %APPDATA%\Claude\claude_
#   # desktop_config.json on Windows):
#   ```json
#   {
#     "mcpServers": {
#       "excel": {
#         "command": "excel-mcp-server"
#       }
#     }
#   }
#   ```
#
#   # Cursor (~/.cursor/mcp.json):
#   ```json
#   {
#     "mcpServers": {
#       "excel": {
#         "command": "excel-mcp-server"
#       }
#     }
#   }
#   ```
#
#   # Via npm + npx (no Go install
#   # required):
#   ```json
#   {
#     "mcpServers": {
#       "excel": {
#         "command": "npx",
#         "args": ["-y", "@negokaz/excel-mcp-server"]
#       }
#     }
#   }
#   ```
#
# Example invocations:
#   # Run the server directly (for
#   # debugging; AI clients normally
#   # launch this)
#   excel-mcp-server
#     # Server runs in stdio mode +
#     # waits for MCP JSON-RPC messages
#     # on stdin
#
#   # The server has no interactive
#   # CLI - operations are invoked by
#   # the AI client through MCP tool
#   # calls
#
# Example MCP tool call (JSON-RPC over
# stdio; sent by AI client):
#   ```json
#   {
#     "jsonrpc": "2.0",
#     "id": 1,
#     "method": "tools/call",
#     "params": {
#       "name": "excel_describe_sheets",
#       "arguments": {
#         "filepath": "/path/to/workbook.xlsx"
#       }
#     }
#   }
#   ```
#
# The xuri/excelize lane is built on
# `github.com/xuri/excelize/v2 v2.9.2`
# (declared verbatim at upstream go.mod
# HEAD as a direct dep, imported by the
# `internal/tools/` package for all
# Excel file operations: sheet
# enumeration + cell read/write + table
# creation + sheet copying + range
# formatting), the canonical Go Excel
# library by Ri Xu (xuri) - github.com/
# xuri/excelize.
#
# xuri/excelize is the de-facto canonical
# Go Excel library:
#   - **Full XLSX read + write** (most
#     comprehensive Go Excel library;
#     handles formulas + charts + pivot
#     tables + cell formatting + images)
#   - **Multi-format support**: XLSX +
#     XLSM (macro-enabled) + XLTM
#     (macro-enabled template) + XLTX
#     (template) + XLAM (add-in)
#   - **Streaming read/write** (memory-
#     efficient for very large
#     workbooks; supports >1M-row
#     workbooks within reasonable
#     memory)
#   - **Pure-Go implementation** (no
#     CGO; no LibreOffice or Excel
#     runtime required)
#   - **Charts + pivot tables** (full
#     chart creation API; pivot table
#     CRUD)
#   - **Cell styling** (font + fill +
#     border + number format +
#     conditional formatting)
#   - **18,000+ stars on github.com/
#     xuri/excelize** (THE highest-
#     star Go Excel library by a wide
#     margin)
#   - **~3,000 reverse-deps on
#     pkg.go.dev (the canonical Go
#     spreadsheet stack)**
#
# excelize's distinguishing position vs
# Go Excel alternatives:
#   - xuri/excelize (Xu): canonical;
#     full read + write; 18k stars;
#     THIS AXIS
#   - tealeg/xlsx: older Go XLSX
#     library; read + write; less
#     comprehensive than excelize;
#     ~6,500 stars
#   - unidoc/unioffice: commercial-
#     backed Office suite (Word +
#     Excel + PowerPoint); freemium
#     model with commercial license
#     for production use
#   - 360EntSecGroup-Skylar/excelize
#     (now redirected to xuri/excelize):
#     the original 360EntSecGroup
#     version moved to Xu's
#     maintenance + the xuri/excelize
#     identity
#
# Ri Xu (xuri / xurime) is a Chinese
# software engineer + the primary
# maintainer of excelize. The project
# originated at 360EntSecGroup (a
# Chinese cybersecurity company)'s
# Skylar team where Xu worked, and Xu
# continued maintaining it after
# leaving for independent work. The
# project's transition from
# `360EntSecGroup-Skylar/excelize` to
# `xuri/excelize` reflects this
# stewardship transfer.
#
# Xu's broader Go ecosystem footprint:
#   - **xuri/excelize** (THIS AXIS;
#     canonical Go Excel library)
#   - **xuri/excelize-wasm** (WebAssembly
#     port of excelize for browser-side
#     Excel manipulation)
#   - **xuri/excelize-py** (Python
#     bindings via FFI)
#   - **xuri/excelize-rb** (Ruby
#     bindings)
#
# Xu's role in Go is *foundational
# Office format infrastructure*. The
# excelize project's cross-language
# bindings (Go + WASM + Python + Ruby)
# represent one of the rare *single-
# author canonical library with
# polyglot bindings* patterns in the
# Office format space.
#
# Multi-axis canonical-Go author/org
# cohort extension (now spanning 31
# distinct individuals/orgs after R1572):
#   - + Ri Xu (xuri; excelize +
#     excelize-wasm + excelize-py +
#     excelize-rb; THIS AXIS;
#     canonical Go Excel library +
#     foundational Office format
#     infrastructure with polyglot
#     bindings)
#
# Xu joining the canonical-Go cohort
# at the *foundational Office format
# infrastructure* level extends the
# pattern of *single-author canonical
# library author with cross-language
# binding maintenance* documented at
# Tuffe's level (Axis 291 Rust;
# calamine + quick-xml).
#
# excel-mcp-server uses excelize for:
#   - Sheet enumeration via OpenFile +
#     GetSheetList APIs
#   - Cell reading via GetCellValue +
#     GetRows APIs
#   - Cell writing via SetCellValue +
#     SetCellStr APIs
#   - Table creation via AddTable
#     API
#   - Sheet duplication via CopySheet
#     API
#   - Range formatting via SetCellStyle
#     + NewStyle APIs
#
# This is the canonical use case for
# excelize in production Go services:
# AI agent backends that need
# spreadsheet manipulation capabilities
# without requiring Excel/LibreOffice
# runtime installation on the server.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 291 :: Excel / spreadsheet
#              processing libraries
#              (XLSX + XLS + ODS file
#              format I/O; cell type
#              handling + multi-sheet
#              workbook enumeration +
#              formula evaluation)
# Round 1572 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 291
#
# Cross-language canonical library family
# for this axis:
#   Rust    : tafia/calamine            [R1571 _rsv]
#             (Johann Tuffe; canonical
#              Rust Excel reader; multi-
#              format XLSX + XLS + XLSB
#              + ODS)
#   Go      : xuri/excelize             [R1572 THIS FILE]
#             (Ri Xu; canonical Go
#              Excel; both read + write;
#              18k stars; ~3k reverse-
#              deps)
#   TS/Node : SheetJS/sheetjs           [R1573 closing]
#             (SheetJS LLC + community;
#              canonical Node spreadsheet
#              library; broadest format
#              support)
#
# Use-case spectrum across the lanes
# (so far):
#   - rsv (Rust, calamine): parallel
#     CSV/TXT/Excel toolkit with
#     unified API
#   - excel-mcp-server (Go, excelize):
#     MCP server exposing Excel
#     read/write capabilities to AI
#     agents via the canonical Model
#     Context Protocol
#
# Both use cases share the *Excel as
# data substrate for downstream tooling*
# pattern - Excel files serve as
# structured data containers that
# specialized tools (analytics CLI or
# AI agent) consume + manipulate.
# Spreadsheets remain THE dominant
# business data format despite many
# alternatives + AI tooling now
# increasingly needs first-class Excel
# integration capabilities.
# ============================================================================

_excel-mcp-server() {
    # excel-mcp-server is a stdio-based MCP
    # server with no command-line flags
    _arguments \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]'
}

_excel-mcp-server "$@"
